y owe to network analysis originally developed in African contexts. On this basis, the contributors adopt and employ concepts from recent studies of Melanesia to analyze contemporary life on the African continent and to explore how this exchange influences the borrowed anthropological perspectives. By focusing on ways in which networks are cut and connections are made, these empirical investigations show how particular relationships are created in today’s Africa. In addition, the volume aims for an approach that recasts relationships between theory and place and concepts and ethnography, in a manner that destabilizes the distinction between fieldwork and writing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aAnthropologyxComparative method. 0aAnthropologyzAfrica. 0aEthnologyzMelanesia. 0aSocial networksxResearchxMethodology. 0aSocial networkszAfrica. 0aSocial sciencesxNetwork analysisxMethodology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aEnglund, Harri, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHultin, Niklas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMyhre, Knut Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMyhre, Knut Christian, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNiehaus, Isak, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReed, Adam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRodima-Taylor, Daivi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSommerfelt, Tone, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVokes, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYarrow, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of 